started with mostly tech/science topics. Second, a broader challenge to

spike with Clubhouse, then it lost repeat users. And Spotify is calling for

The problem that we are trying to solve is reducing the pain of reading
that some people feel, while keeping the enjoyment of learning. I listen to
a lot of podcasts to learn, but struggle to sit down and read. With
RoundTable, the idea is that you can convert, say, a 50 page research paper
into a personalized podcast so that, rather than spending an hour or 2
reading the paper, you can listen to a short podcast conversation between
two AIs breaking down the paper. The RoundTable podcast is also
interactive, so you can interrupt if you want to redirect the conversation
to a different topic or ask a question. Although I have learned a ton from
podcasts, I have found myself looking for podcasts on more niche topics
that aren't available or don't talk about what I want, which is where the
idea for a generative podcast stemmed from.

I'm very curious to hear your thoughts on and discuss different niches. We
originally set out to build this for college students because we felt this
pain as students, but this space is becoming increasingly saturated with
different AI apps. I have a lot of other ideas for where this idea of
personalized podcasts can be applied, but I also think there is still a
significant amount of room in education.

priorMessage:
Hey Alexander,

I enjoyed meeting you yesterday.  After we talked I had another thought
about something to mention that you could consider doing to broaden your
connections with tech companies and job opportunities.  There's a place in
NYC called the Recurse Center (recurse.com) that's like a retreat center
for people who are either starting a career in tech, or looking to make a
change to their tech career. It's a little hard to describe, but the
website has a pretty good writeup about it.  Basically, participants spend
a few weeks working on projects together and networking with each other,
with the staff, and with recruiters at various tech companies.  After you
complete the program, the staff helps you find a job.  There's no cost to
participants, other than paying your own travel & living expenses if you go
to NYC for it (see below for more on that).  It's a great way to make lots
of connections, and there's an active community of Recurse Center alumni
who keep in touch with each other on an ongoing basis. My wife Andrea did
it -- it was the thing that got us to move to NYC in the first place, and
it was the connections she made there that led to her getting several job
offers.  I ended up meeting many people who did it in NYC, and they all
loved it and benefited from it hugely.

At the time that Andrea went through their program (in 2014), it was
in-person only, but ever since the covid pandemic they also have a virtual
option, so I don't think it'd be completely necessary to actually travel to
NYC for it, although I think there would be advantages to doing so.  (You
mentioned you didn't feel particularly attracted to NYC, which I can
certainly understand.  That's how I felt before we moved there, but living
there completely changed my view of it -- I ended up really enjoying it.
I'll be happy to chat with you more about that if you like.)

Also, when we talked yesterday I mentioned another Davidson alum named Will
Sommers, who works at Facebook/Meta in NYC and suggested you connect with
him.  His email address is will.sommers@gmail.com; I mentioned you to him
yesterday and he said he'd be happy to chat with you, so feel free to reach
out to him.  He also went through the Recurse Center program -- that's how
Andrea and I met him -- and I'm sure he'll be happy to tell you all about
it if you chat with him.

If you do read about the Recurse Center and would like to hear more about
it, Andrea would also be happy to chat with you about her experience there.

--Mark

Wells Fargo Team Members’ Dependent Children Scholarship Program

July 31, 2020

ID# 2020-636157

Dear Alexander Donald:

Congratulations!  On behalf of Wells Fargo, I am pleased to announce you have been selected to receive a $1,000.00 Wells Fargo Team Members’ Dependent Children scholarship to be used for all education related expenses. You must meet all eligibility requirements including enrolling in a full-time undergraduate course of study at Davidson College or another accredited two-or four-year college or university or vocational school for the entire 2020-21 academic year.

Your Responsibilities:
* To receive your award, complete the on-line Scholarship Acceptance Form (SAF) at https://award-acceptance.scholarshipamerica.org/index.php?program=WELLS&year=2020&pub=1 by August 8, 2020.  You will need the information below in order to complete the form successfully.  Your first name, application ID and Date of Birth must match what was originally submitted on your application.

Application ID: 636157
First Name (as listed above)
Official Date of Birth
* Email a digital head and shoulders photo to segments@wellsfargo.com (mailto:segments@wellsfargo.com) .
* Notify your college of the award by providing them with a copy of this official notification and save it for future reference.
* A note of appreciation for your award may be sent to Attn: Gretchen Lennon, Wells Fargo Corporate HR, 550 South 4th Street, MAC N9310-110, Minneapolis, MN 55415.
* If your college choice, enrollment plans, or permanent home address change after you submit the SAF, promptly email us.

Important Information:
* The award will be processed in one installment in mid-August.  Based on your school choice, the check will be payable to your school and is to be equally split between fall and spring terms.  It will be mailed to your permanent home address.  Please allow 10 business days for delivery.
* A renewal form will be sent by email to you in January. Your award is renewable up to the graduation date reported on your application and up to a maximum of three years or until a bachelor’s degree is earned, whichever occurs first provided Wells Fargo continues the scholarship program. Renewal is based on maintaining satisfactory academic performance, in a full-time undergraduate program and continued parent employment with Wells Fargo.
* Undergraduate awards may not transfer to graduate study, however you may reapply to the program for a graduate study award.
* The total maximum number of years you may receive an award is 6 years, including past recipient years.
* The reporting of your scholarship award for income tax reporting purposes is your responsibility.  Please consult a tax advisor to inform you of your reporting obligations.


Scholarship America administers this program according to guidelines established by Wells Fargo.  If you have questions, please contact us and refer to the Wells Fargo Team Members’ Dependent Children Scholarship Program.

Sincerely,

Deidra Willson
Program Manager
Scholarship America
Email: wellsfargo@scholarshipamerica.org

Additional Resources

Beyond College: Wells Fargo Webinars
Covering a wide range of topics, from personal finances to professional development, the Beyond College Webinar series will help better prepare you for what's next after college. To listen, replay or register for the event, please visit: https://collegesteps.wf.com/. If prompted, registrants should enter passcode wellsfargo2020 (all lowercase) to register for or listen to the playback of each webinar.
